article.headline: Oregon 62, Portland State 55
article.story: EUGENE, Ore. (AP) -- Oregon was playing for the first time in 11 days -- and the rust showed. The Ducks failed to take advantage of Portland State's first-half futility and had to hold off a late rally to beat the Vikings 62-55 on Tuesday. Luke Jackson scored 22 points, including 14 in the second half, Ian Crosswhite scored 14 points on 7-of-10 shooting and Brandon Lincoln added 12 to lead Oregon (2-0) to its 23rd consecutive nonconference win at home. "We just need to play some games," Oregon head coach Ernie Kent said. "We need to get after things. We fought our way through some rust and did what we needed to do, which was win." Seth Scott led Portland State with 15 points before fouling out in the final minute. Sheu Oduniyi added 11 for the Vikings (1-3), who lost their 18th consecutive road game. Jackson scored 10 points in the first nine minutes of the second half as the Ducks stretched a 28-22 halftime lead into a 48-34 advantage with 11:04 to play. But it wasn't enough to put the Vikings away. Seamus Boxley and Scott scored four points each to spark an 11-3 run as Portland State cut the deficit to 51-45 with 4:53 left. A Boxley tip-in with 3:30 to play pulled the Vikings to within 52-48. But that was as close as they would come. The Ducks converted all 10 of their free throws down the stretch to secure the win. "You have to play perfect basketball every night, against every team," Jackson said. "That comes with experience." The Ducks committed 11 first-half turnovers and were unable to take full advantage of a 13-minute stretch where the Vikings failed to score a field goal. The Vikings took a 12-9 lead, but missed their next 13 attempts from the field before Oduniyi hit a 3-pointer with 1:20 left in the half. The Vikings recovered from the dry spell, however, outscoring the Ducks 8-1 to cut the lead to six at the break. Led by Jackson's eight rebounds, the Ducks won the battle of the boards, 35-29. Each team gave the other plenty of freebies, as Oregon committed 20 turnovers and the Vikings 16. "Portland State gave a gutsy effort," Kent said. "They had us well scouted and were ready to play." ^
